    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "When a file transfer fails, there is no (direct) way for a receiving client to see that it's failed - it just appears completed.  Normally on the completion of a file, the callback set by tox_callback_file_recv_chunk () will pass a chunk length of 0.  When a file transfer fails, the callback simply stops being called.\r\n\r\nI would suggest that the callback to receive a position of 0, with a length of 0 after a timeout (perhaps 30 seconds?) within the c-toxcore protocol to indicate failure so the recipient realizes the file that was being received wasn't entirely received.\r\n\r\nOtherwise, the client can implement this with an appropriate timeout, but I think it's best if the client's work is minimized.",
    "closed_at": "2022-02-06T11:47:12Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "A client has enough information about the file transfer to easily accomplish this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nmain_loop() {\r\n    for each ft in file_transfers {\r\n        if (ft.last_chunk_size != 0 && timed_out(ft.time_last_received_chunk, TIMEOUT_INTERVAL)) {\r\n           ft.abort(); \r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo do this properly we would need to add additional config options so that clients can customize this behaviour (clients may not want timeouts, or may want something other than the default). I don't see any reason to add more complexity to an already complex API for the sake of saving clients a couple lines of code.",
